### To Install the Virtual Environment

Step1:- Create a project directory
$mkdir Environments

Step2:- Change into the project directory
$cd Environments

Step3:- Create Virtual Environment according to specify Python Version you required
Step3.1:- For Python 2 version:- Run "virtualenv <name_of_virtualenv>"
$virtualenv <name_of_virtualenv>

Step3.2:- For Python 3 version:- Run "python3 -m venv <name_of_virtualenv>"
$ python3 -m venv <name_of_virtualenv>
Note If "venv" is not install then install it "sudo apt-get install python3-venv"

Step3.3:- If you want to install some specific version i.e 2.6 or 3.2:- Run "virtualenv -p /path/of/python/python2.6 env_name"
$ virtualenv -p /usr/bin/python2.6 py26_env


Step4:- source <name_of_virtualenv>/bin/activate
$source <name_of_virtualenv>/bin/activate

Step5:- To check the Python Version and list of Package
$ which python #Check Python Version
$ python -V #Check Python Version
$ pip list     #See all package install

Step5:- deactivate
### How to use in future
Step1:- souce <name_of_virtualenv>/bin/activate
To Deactivate
Step2:- deactivate

Steps Others:-
Step Save the package version in "requirements.txt":- "pip freeze --local >file_name.txt"
$ pip freeze --local > requirements.txt

